Constructor in java

[Constructor in java](https://www.flowerbrackets.com/constructor-in-java/)

Constructor is a block of code used to initialize objects.

NOTE:

constructor does not have any return type.
constructor name is same as class name.
constructor is called when an object of a classs is created.
access modifiers applicable for constructors are public, private, protected and default.
constructor gets called when we write “new()” keyword.
Syntax:

class DemoClass
{
   // constructor name is same as class name
   DemoClass()
   {
      ....
   }
}
// calls DemoClass() constructor
DemoClass obj = new DemoClass();

Example

public class ConstructorDemo
{
   int a; // class attribute
   // create constructor for class ConstructorDemo
   ConstructorDemo()
   {
      a = 26; // initial value for class attribute 'a'
   }
   public static void main(String[] args)
   {
      // creating object for ConstructorDemo class
      // here we're calling constructor ConstructorDemo()
      ConstructorDemo obj = new ConstructorDemo();
      System.out.println(obj.a);
   }
}


Output:

26
